The Literary Magic of Harry Potter
Princeton — This summer, readers around the world celebrated the 20th anniversary of the first book in J.K. Rowling's Harry Potter series — Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone (renamed Harry Potter and the Sorcerer's Stone in the United States) — at literary festivals and bookstores. They had every reason to celebrate.
Since June 26, 1997, when this young wizard first appeared, the "Boy Who Lived" has become a symbol of resilience and perseverance.
Over the past 20 years, the Harry Potter series has expanded to include seven novels, been translated into more than 70 languages, and has sold a combined total of 450 million copies.
The eight movies based on this book have grossed a cumulative $7 billion, while Harry Potter-themed toys and merchandise have generated an additional $7 billion in revenue.
It is difficult for people of a certain age and those with a literary mindset to imagine a day when global audiences are not captivated by Rowling's works.
Thus, I am always amazed when I recall my students' poor reaction to Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone in the fall of 1999, when I included the book in the syllabus for my popular literature course at Princeton University. I have been teaching the "Bestsellers in America" course series since 1993.
The course examines popular works from the 17th century to the present, inviting students to consider why and how these bestsellers have attracted their audiences.
At the end of each semester, I have my students choose a final work that represents popular taste.
In 1999, they chose the first Harry Potter novel.
That year, the Potter fever hit the American coast hard.
In June, the American publisher of the series urgently pushed the hardcover edition of the second book in the Harry Potter series, *Harry Potter and the Chamber of Secrets*, into bookstores.
The institution also published the third book in the series, *Harry Potter and the Prisoner of Azkaban*, as well as the paperback edition of *Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone*, on September 8.
By the end of the month, Rowling's novel had topped the *New York Times* bestseller list, with the paperback edition of *Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone* claiming the number one spot on the paperback sales chart.
Time magazine even featured the bespectacled wizard on its cover.
Harry Potter's image is visible everywhere within sight.
My students couldn't wait to find out why such a fever had taken hold.
My goodness, they were utterly disappointed.
In their eyes, the Harry Potter series was nothing more than second-rate nonsense, far inferior to the cherished series of their childhood memories such as *The Chronicles of Narnia* or *The Lord of the Rings*.
Although their childhood had only just passed a few years ago, they condemned Harry Potter, just like many notorious adult critics, with terms such as "fabricated," "poorly written," "clichéd," and "boring."
In their eyes, the Harry Potter series was nothing more than second-rate nonsense, far inferior to the cherished series of their childhood memories such as *The Chronicles of Narnia* or *The Lord of the Rings*.
In their eyes, Harry possessed neither miracles, nor wit, nor warmth.
I was surprised by the students'反感, but in hindsight, there was nothing really to be surprised about.
Although adults had always formed a significant part of the Harry Potter audience, these students were precisely in the wrong age group to objectively understand the Harry Potter phenomenon.
They had passed the age of accepting new children's literature, yet they were too young to have their own children (at the time, I had just become a parent myself), and they eagerly insisted that although the Harry Potter series was now wildly popular, it would soon be forgotten by people.
The following autumn, in 2000, the next batch of students also chose *Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone* as their final analysis work, just like their predecessors, confidently refusing to accept the book.
Let's fast forward to spring 2007.
After setting the course aside for a few years, I taught "Bestsellers in America" again.
When students chose their final analysis work, they selected *Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone*.
And I was ready to face their criticism.
But this time, their comments were very positive.
These were a new generation of students, born between 1986 and 1989, who first encountered Rowling's work not as university students but as teenagers in their early teens, just beginning to enter adolescence. This meant they grew up into young adults alongside Harry, Ron, and Hermione.
The same thing happened again in the fall of 2010.
"For these students, 'We grew up with Harry Potter' has become a motto rather than a label."
Will Harry fade from memory?
As long as we are alive, it is impossible.
I have taught the bestsellers course twice since 2010, and both times the students chose non-Harry Potter novels for their final reviews.
Is it boredom with Potter?
From the reviews Harry's series received in another course I taught on children's literature, this seems unlikely.
Now, I have chosen to include a Harry Potter novel in the syllabus, but I did not select *Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone*, instead I chose *Harry Potter and the Prisoner of Azkaban*—which is my favorite of the seven Harry Potter novels, marking the series' transition from children's literature to young adult fiction, with complex portrayals of loyalty, betrayal, anger, and compassion.
Many of my students also favor this book.
But how long will the popularity of the Harry Potter series last?
Each time I teach children's literature, I first conduct a poll: "Which books on the syllabus did you read during your childhood?"
In 2010, 86% of people had read *Harry Potter and the Prisoner of Azkaban*.
In 2012, this figure rose to 94%.
But in the following years, the percentage continued to decline — 87% in 2014, and dropping to 81% in 2016.
These are not sciences, I know.
But I'm curious: when I teach "Children's Literature" again in the spring of next year, will the percentage of students who have read Harry Potter drop below 80%?
Will the facts prove that the students of 1999 to 2000 were right, that Harry Potter's status continues to decline and will never become a timeless classic?
Is there still a balance point ahead where the percentage can stabilize and stop declining?
Perhaps Harry's 40th anniversary will tell us the answer.
I was glad to have invited him into my classroom all along until then.
